nal name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form o